sentences: Michael White (born November 29, 1954 in New Orleans) is a jazz clarinetist, bandleader, composer, jazz historian and musical educator.
White can be heard on the 1989 album The Majesty of the Blues by Wynton Marsalis.
Marsalis appears on White's 1990 album Crescent City Serenade with  Wendell Brunious and Walter Payton.
Since 1979 White has played in the Young Tuxedo Brass Band, founded by clarinetist John Casimir sometime in the 1940s.

During the 1980s he led a band called The New Orleans Hot Seven.
Performing "A Tribute to Jelly Roll Morton" in concert with them at the Lincoln Center in New York City in 1989 led to a favorable review by Jon Pareles in the New York Times.
On May 25, 2004, a selection from White's album Dancing in the Sky ("Algiers Hoodoo Woman") was broadcast on NPR's All Songs Considered.
In 1981, White founded The Original Liberty Jazz Band to preserve the musical heritage of New Orleans.
On May 13, 2006, White performed "Just a Closer Walk With Thee" at the Tulane University commencement ceremony.
White was living in a one-story home in the Gentilly district of New Orleans, near the London Avenue Canal during Hurricane Katrina in 2005.

He was discovered by Kid Sheik Colar, who heard him performing in Jackson Square in the French Quarter.
The group has performed an end-of-year concert at the Village Vanguard every year since the early 1990s.
White is also a college professor who formerly taught Spanish, now teaching African-American music at Xavier University of Louisiana, an historically black university.
White was a collector of jazz artifacts and local history for 30 years.
